To solve this, we first need to understand that the Fibonacci sequence is recursively defined.
\[
\text{Fibonacci } n=\left \{ 
\begin{array}{cc} 
1, & n = 0 \\ 
1, & n = 1 \\ 
\text{Fibonacci } (n-1) + \text{Fibonacci } (n-2), & n > 1 \\ 
\end{array}
\right. 
\end{array}
{/eq}

To get the remainders when dividing the terms by 8, we look at mod 8 added to the last two remainders. The first few iterations will yield a new cycle, as the remainders reset after a certain point.
\[
\begin{array}{rrrrrrrrrrrr}
1, & 1, & 2, & 3, & 5, & 0, & 5, & 5, & 2, & 7,\\
0, & 7, & 7, & 6, & 5, & 3, & 0, & 3, & 3, & 6
\end{array}
\]

After 20 iterations, the same remainders are present. So, to find the remainder of the $100^{\mathrm{th}}$ Fibonacci number when divided by 8, we can find the remainder of 100 modulo 20. Then, we find the remainder of the Fibonacci number at that position in the cycle. In this case, the remainder of the $100^{\mathrm{th}}$ Fibonacci number when divided by 8 is 0.

